and the widespread Human race, weakly slumped <br>
down at a table, some distance from the bar.  She<br>
was sick, and she sweated with fever and chills.<br>
<br>
She did not understand.  Why did the Gnolls of<br>
Blackburrow despise her?  She worshipped the<br>
same god they did, so why did they scowl at her,<br>
always prepared to attack whenever she came near?<br>
<br>
Angrily, and with tears coming to her eyes, the young<br>
Priestess remembered her day in the Lair of the<br>
Blackburrow Beasts, also known as the Sabertooths.<br>
<br>
Atrilinea had been trying to elicit SOME sort of response<br>
from the gnolls besides growling and attacking.  She<br>
would not have minded if those foul creatures demanded<br>
she clean up their dung, if only to get in their good graces.<br>
Unfortunately, the Sabertooths of Blackburrow seemed<br>
to hate Humans, even if they followed the Lord of Disease.<br>
<br>
With a sneeze, she remembered her torturer.  Shaman,<br>
indeed.  With his skills, the Gnoll should have been a<br>
Necromancer.  He was the one who had caused her ills.<br>
<br>
A careless fighter in Blackburrow was after the paw<br>
and the rusty warhammer of that Gnoll High Shaman.<br>
Atrilinea was on the top level of the lair, trying to plead<br>
with the scrawnies.  Suddenly, a swarm of the diseased<br>
dogs ran up to her place and began snarling loudly.<br>
<br>
Before she knew what was happening, the Shaman,<br>
the object of the protective swarm, cast a Sickening <br>
spell upon her.  Atrilinea sweated and shivered, feeling<br>
very feverish.  Even though the worst of it had passed,<br>
she was still feeling very ill.  She lay her head down<br>
on her arms, convulsing lightly with hot shock.<br>
<br>
Why did the Gnolls not accept her?  Before now,<br>
the Cleric had thought that all of the Plaguebringer's<br>
children tolerated one another.  Apparently, this was<br>
not true.<br>
<br>
Atrilinea hoped the barmaid would give her something<br>
warm and poisonously alcoholic to help her forget. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
